Anatase TiO2 has a tetragonal structure (space group I41/amd), in which a Ti4+ ion is surrounded by a distorted oxygen octahedron while numerous vacant octahedral and tetrahedral sites exist between these octahedrons. Li ions are accommodated in these vacant sites. Two voltage plateaus appear near 1.7 and 1.9 V (vs. Li/Li+) in the curves of the anatase TNAs and MoO3/TNAs anodes, which demonstrate that TNAs are also contributing in MoO3/TNAs while they are totally different from porous MoO3. The one at 1.7 V (vs. Li/Li+) in the negative scan corresponds to Li-ion insertion into TiO2, while the other in the positive scan accords with Li-ion desertion. The total reaction for Li-ion insertion/extraction is described by (Guan et al. 2014a, b):1TiO2+xLi++xe-↔LixTiO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
